# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pseudorandomness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Randomness has multiple uses in science, art, statistics, cryptography, gaming, gambling, and other fields.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] For example, random assignment in randomized controlled trials helps scientists to test hypotheses, and random numbers or pseudorandom numbers help video games such as video poker.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] These uses have different levels of requirements, which leads to the use of different methods.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Mathematically, there are distinctions between randomization, pseudorandomization, and quasirandomization, as well as between random number generators and pseudorandom number generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] For example, applications in cryptography usually have strict requirements, whereas other uses (such as generating a "quote of the day") can use a looser standard of pseudorandomness.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Unpredictable (by the humans involved) numbers (usually taken to be random numbers) were first investigated in the context of gambling developing, sometimes, pathological forms like apophenia.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Multiple randomizing devices such as dice, shuffling playing cards, and roulette wheels, seem to have been developed for use in games of chance.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Electronic gambling equipment cannot use these and so theoretical problems are less easy to avoid; methods of creating them are sometimes regulated by governmental gaming commissions.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Modern electronic casino games contain often one or more random number generators which decide the outcome of a trial in the game.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Even in modern slot machines, where mechanical reels seem to spin on the screen, the reels are actually spinning for entertainment value only.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] They eventually stop exactly where the machine's software decided they would stop when the handle was first pulled.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Some thefts from casinos have used clever modifications of internal software to bias the outcomes of the machines—at least in those which have been discovered.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Gambling establishments keep close track of machine payouts in an attempt to detect such alterations.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Random draws are often used to make a decision where no rational or fair basis exists for making a deterministic decision, or to make unpredictable moves.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Fifth century BC Athenian democracy developed out of a notion of isonomia (equality of political rights), and random selection was a principal way of achieving this fairness.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Greek democracy (literally meaning "rule by the people") was actually run by the people: administration was in the hands of committees allotted from the people and regularly changed.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Although it may seem strange to those used to modern liberal democracy, the Athenian Greeks considered elections to be essentially undemocratic.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] This was because citizens chosen on merit or popularity contradicted the democratic equality of all citizenry.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] In addition, allotment prevented the corrupt practice of buying votes as no one could know who would be selected as a magistrate, or to sit on a jury.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Allotment, also called sortition, is today used in the selection of jurors in Anglo-Saxon legal systems like the UK and United States.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Proposals have been made for its use in government such as a new constitution for Iraq and various proposals for Upper Houses chosen by allotment—see Reform of the House of Lords § Allotment (sortition).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Scholars have studied the potential of random selection of personnel in politics and organizations.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Random numbers have uses in physics such as electronic noise studies, engineering, and operations research.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Multiple methods of statistical analysis, such as the bootstrap method, require random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Monte Carlo methods in physics and computer science require random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Statistical practice is based on statistical theory which is, itself, founded on the concept of randomness.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] A number of elements of statistical practice depend on randomness via random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Where those random numbers fail to be actually random, any subsequent statistical analysis may suffer from systematic bias.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Elements of statistical practice that depend on randomness include: choosing a representative sample of the population being examined, disguising the protocol of a study from a participant (see randomized controlled trial) and Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] These applications are useful in auditing (for determining samples - such as invoices) and experimental design (for example in the creation of double-blind trials).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Many experiments in physics rely on a statistical analysis of their output.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] For example, an experiment might collect X-rays from an astronomical source and then analyze the result for periodic signals.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Since random noise can be expected to appear to have faint periodic signals embedded in it, statistical analysis is required to determine the likelihood that a detected signal actually represents a genuine signal.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Such analysis methods requires the generation of random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] If the statistical method is extremely sensitive to patterns in the data (such as those used to search for binary pulsars), large amounts of data with no recognizable pattern are needed.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] In multiple scientific and engineering fields, computer simulations of real phenomena are commonly used.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] When the real phenomena are affected by unpredictable processes, such as radio noise or day-to-day weather, these processes can be simulated using random or pseudo-random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Automatic random number generators were first constructed to carry out computer simulation of physical phenomena, notably simulation of neutron transport in nuclear fission.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Pseudo-random numbers are frequently used in simulation of statistical events, a simple example being the outcome of tossing a coin.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] More complicated situations are simulation of population genetics, or the behaviour of sub-atomic particles.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Such simulation methods, often called stochastic methods, have a number of applications in computer simulation of real-world processes.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Some more speculative projects, such as the Global Consciousness Project, monitor fluctuations in the randomness of numbers generated by multiple hardware random number generators in an attempt to predict the scope of an event in near future.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] The intent is to prove that large-scale events that are about to happen build up a "pressure" which affects the RNGs.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] A ubiquitous use of unpredictable random numbers is in cryptography, which underlies most of the schemes which attempt to provide security in modern communications (e.g., confidentiality, authentication, electronic commerce, etc.).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] For example, if a user wants to use an encryption algorithm, it is best that they select a random number as the key.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] The selection must have high entropy (i.e., unpredictability) to any attacker, thus increasing attack difficulty.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] With keys having low entropy (i.e., relatively easily guessable by attackers), security is likely to be compromised.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] To illustrate, imagine if a simple 32 bit linear congruential pseudo-random number generator of the type supplied with most programming languages (e.g., as the 'rand' or 'rnd' function) is used as a source of keys.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] There will only be some four billion possible values produced before the generator repeats itself.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] A suitably motivated adversary could simply test them all; this is practical as of 2010, using readily available computers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Even if a linear congruential RNG is used with 1000-bit parameters, it is a simple exercise in linear algebra to recover the modulus m, and the constants a and b, where x' = ax +b (mod m), given only five consecutive values.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Even if a better random number generator is used, it might be insecure (e.g., the seed might be guessable), producing predictable keys and reducing security to nil.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Truly random numbers are absolutely required to be assured of the theoretical security provided by the one-time pad — the only provably unbreakable encryption algorithm.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Furthermore, those random sequences cannot be reused and must never become available to any attacker, which implies a continuously operable generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] See Venona for an example of what happens when these requirements are violated when using a one-time pad.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] For cryptographic purposes, one normally assumes some upper limit on the work an adversary can do (usually this limit is astronomically sized).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] If one has a pseudo-random number generator whose output is "sufficiently difficult" to predict, one can generate true random numbers to use as the initial value (i.e., the seed), and then use the pseudo-random number generator to produce numbers for use in cryptographic applications.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Such random number generators are called cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generators, and several have been implemented (for example, the /dev/urandom device available on most Unixes, the Yarrow and Fortuna designs, server, and AT&T Bell Laboratories "truerand").
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] As with all cryptographic software, there are subtle issues beyond those discussed here, so care is certainly indicated in actual practice.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] In any case, it is sometimes impossible to avoid the need for true (i.e., hardware-based) random number generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Since a requirement in cryptography is high entropy, *any* published random sequence is a poor choice, as are such sequences as the digits in an irrational number such as the φ or even in transcendental numbers such as π, or e.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] All are available to an enterprising attacker.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Put another way, in cryptography, random bit streams need to be not only random, but also secret and hence unpredictable.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Public or third-party sources of random values, or random values computed from publicly observable phenomena (weather, sports game results, stock prices), are almost never cryptographically acceptable.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Their use may be tempting, but in reality, they permit easier attacks than attacking the cryptography.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Since most cryptographic applications require a few thousand bits at most, slow random number generators serve well—if they are actually random.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] This use of random generators is important; some informed observers believe every computer should have a way to generate true random numbers.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Some aesthetic theories claim to be based on randomness in one way or another.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Little testing is done in these situations, and so claims of reliance on and use of randomness are generally poorly based in definite theory and more on an impression of randomness from technical fields.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] An example of a need for randomness sometimes occurs in arranging items in an art exhibit.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Usually this is avoided by using a theme.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] As John Cage pointed out, "While there are many ways that sounds might be produced [i.e., in terms of patterns], few are attempted".
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Similarly, the arrangement of art in exhibits is often deliberately non-random.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] One case of this was Hitler's attempt to portray modern art in the worst possible light by arranging works in worst possible manner.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] A case can be made for trying to make art in the worst possible way; i.e., either as anti-art, or as actually random art.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Dadaism, as well as other movements in art and letters, has attempted to accommodate and acknowledge randomness in various ways.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Often people mistake order for randomness based on lack of information; e.g., Jackson Pollock's drip paintings, Helen Frankenthaler's abstractions (e.g., "For E.M.").
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Thus, in some theories of art, all art is random in that it's "just paint and canvas" (the explanation of Frank Stella's work).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Similarly, the "unexpected" ending is part of the nature of interesting literature.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] An example of this is Denis Diderot's novel *Jacques le fataliste* (literally: *James the Fatalist*; sometimes referred to as *Jacques the Fatalist* or *Jacques the Servant and his Master*).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Diderot was making the point that the novel (then a recent introduction to European literature) seemed random (in the sense of being invented out of thin air by the author, not in a modern technical sense).
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] See also Eugenio Montale, Theatre of the Absurd.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Randomness in music includes John Cage's chance-derived *Music of Changes*, stochastic music, aleatoric music, indeterminate music, or generative music.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Random numbers are also used in situations where "fairness" is approximated by randomization, such as selecting jurors and military draft lotteries.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Random numbers are often used in parapsychology as a test of precognition.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Other examples include selecting, or generating, a "Random Quote of the Day" for a website, or determining which way a villain might move in a computer game.
[src:pseudorandomness/applications-of-randomness] Weaker forms of *randomness* are also closely associated with hash algorithms and in creating amortized searching and sorting algorithms.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In graph theory, an **expander graph** is a sparse graph that has strong connectivity properties, quantified using vertex, edge or spectral expansion.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Expander constructions have spawned research in pure and applied mathematics, with several applications to complexity theory, design of robust computer networks, and the theory of error-correcting codes.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Intuitively, an expander graph is a finite, undirected multigraph in which every subset of the vertices that is not "too large" has a "large" boundary.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Different formalisations of these notions give rise to different notions of expanders: *edge expanders*, *vertex expanders*, and *spectral expanders*, as defined below.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] A disconnected graph is not an expander, since the boundary of a connected component is empty.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Every connected finite graph is an expander; however, different connected graphs have different expansion parameters.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The complete graph has the best expansion property, but it has largest possible degree.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Informally, a graph is a good expander if it has low degree and high expansion parameters.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] the edges between the subsets of vertices *A*,*B* ⊆ *V*(*G*).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In the equation, the minimum is over all nonempty sets S of at most *n*⁄2 vertices and ∂*S* is the *edge boundary* of S, i.e., the set of edges with exactly one endpoint in S.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] is the minimum number of edges that need to be cut in order to split the graph in two.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The edge expansion normalizes this concept by dividing with smallest number of vertices among the two parts.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] To see how the normalization can drastically change the value, consider the following example.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Take two complete graphs with the same number of vertices n and add n edges between the two graphs by connecting their vertices one-to-one.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The minimum cut will be n but the edge expansion will be 1.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Notice that in min |∂*S*|, the optimization can be equivalently done either over 0 ≤ |*S*| ≤ *n*⁄2 or over any non-empty subset, since $E(S,{\overline {S}})=E({\overline {S}},S)$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The same is not true for *h*(*G*) because of the normalization by |*S*|.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] where ∂out(*S*) is the *outer boundary* of S, i.e., the set of vertices in *V*(*G*) \ *S* with at least one neighbor in S.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In a variant of this definition (called *unique neighbor expansion*) ∂out(*S*) is replaced by the set of vertices in V with *exactly* one neighbor in S.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] where $\partial _{\text{in}}(S)$ is the *inner boundary* of S, i.e., the set of vertices in S with at least one neighbor in *V*(*G*) \ *S*.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] When G is d-regular, a linear algebraic definition of expansion is possible based on the eigenvalues of the adjacency matrix *A* = *A*(*G*) of G, where Aij is the number of edges between vertices i and j.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Because A is symmetric, the spectral theorem implies that A has n real-valued eigenvalues *λ*1 ≥ *λ*2 ≥ … ≥ *λ**n*.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] It is known that all these eigenvalues are in [−*d*, *d*] and more specifically, it is known that *λ**n* = −*d* if and only if G is bipartite.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The bound given by an (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graph on *λ**i* for *i* ≠ 1 is useful in many contexts, including the expander mixing lemma.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Spectral expansion can be *two-sided*, as above, with $\max _{i\neq 1}|\lambda _{i}|\leq \lambda$ , or it can be *one-sided*, with $\max _{i\neq 1}\lambda _{i}\leq \lambda$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The latter is a weaker notion that holds also for bipartite graphs and is still useful for many applications, such as the Alon–Chung lemma.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Because G is regular, the uniform distribution $u\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with *ui* = 1⁄*n* for all *i* = 1, …, *n* is the stationary distribution of G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] That is, we have *Au* = *du*, and u is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue *λ*1 = *d*, where d is the degree of the vertices of G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The *spectral gap* of G is defined to be *d* − *λ*2, and it measures the spectral expansion of the graph G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] is the 2-norm of the vector $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The normalized versions of these definitions are also widely used and more convenient in stating some results.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Here one considers the matrix ⁠1/*d*⁠*A*, which is the Markov transition matrix of the graph G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] For not necessarily regular graphs, the spectrum of a graph can be defined similarly using the eigenvalues of the Laplacian matrix.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] For directed graphs, one considers the singular values of the adjacency matrix A, which are equal to the roots of the eigenvalues of the symmetric matrix *A*T*A*.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] A family $(G_{i})_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ of d -regular graphs of increasing size is an **expander family** if $h(G_{i})$ is bounded away from zero.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The expansion parameters defined above are related to each other.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Consequently, for constant degree graphs, vertex and edge expansion are qualitatively the same.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] When G is d-regular, meaning each vertex is of degree d, there is a relationship between the isoperimetric constant *h*(*G*) and the gap *d* − *λ*2 in the spectrum of the adjacency operator of G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] By standard spectral graph theory, the trivial eigenvalue of the adjacency operator of a d-regular graph is *λ*1 = *d* and the first non-trivial eigenvalue is *λ*2.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The lower bound is achieved in limit for the hypercube Qn, where *h*(*G*) = 1 and *d* – *λ*2 = 2.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] These inequalities are closely related to the Cheeger bound for Markov chains and can be seen as a discrete version of Cheeger's inequality in Riemannian geometry.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Asymptotically speaking, the quantities *h*2⁄*d*, *h*out, and *h*in2 are all bounded above by the spectral gap *O*(*d* – *λ*2).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] There are four general strategies for explicitly constructing families of expander graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The first strategy is algebraic and group-theoretic, the second strategy is analytic and uses additive combinatorics, the third strategy is combinatorial and uses the zig-zag and related graph products, and the fourth strategy is based on lifts.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Noga Alon showed that certain graphs constructed from finite geometries are the sparsest examples of highly expanding graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Algebraic constructions based on Cayley graphs are known for various variants of expander graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The following construction is due to Margulis and has been analysed by Gabber and Galil.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] By a theorem of Alon and Boppana, all sufficiently large d-regular graphs satisfy $\lambda _{2}\geq 2{\sqrt {d-1}}-o(1)$ , where *λ*2 is the second largest eigenvalue in absolute value.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] As a direct consequence, we know that for every fixed d and $\lambda <2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ , there are only finitely many (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Hence Ramanujan graphs have an asymptotically smallest possible value of *λ*2.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] This makes them excellent spectral expanders.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Lubotzky, Phillips, and Sarnak (1988), Margulis (1988), and Morgenstern (1994) show how Ramanujan graphs can be constructed explicitly.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In 1985, Alon, conjectured that most d-regular graphs on n vertices, for sufficiently large n, are almost Ramanujan.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] A simpler proof of a slightly weaker result was given by Puder.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Marcus, Spielman and Srivastava, gave a construction of bipartite Ramanujan graphs based on lifts.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Reingold, Vadhan, and Wigderson introduced the zig-zag product in 2000.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Roughly speaking, the zig-zag product of two expander graphs produces a graph with only slightly worse expansion.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Therefore, a zig-zag product can also be used to construct families of expander graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Note that property (1) implies that the zig-zag product of two expander graphs is also an expander graph, thus zig-zag products can be used inductively to create a family of expander graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Intuitively, the construction of the zig-zag product can be thought of in the following way.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Each vertex of G is blown up to a "cloud" of m vertices, each associated to a different edge connected to the vertex.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Each vertex is now labeled as (*v*, *k*) where v refers to an original vertex of G and k refers to the kth edge of v.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Two vertices, (*v*, *k*) and (*w*,*ℓ*) are connected if it is possible to get from (*v*, *k*) to (*w*, *ℓ*) through the following sequence of moves.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Jump across clouds using edge k' in G to get to (*w*, *ℓ′*).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] An r-lift of a graph is formed by replacing each vertex by r vertices, and each edge by a matching between the corresponding sets of r vertices.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The lifted graph inherits the eigenvalues of the original graph, and has some additional eigenvalues.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Bilu and Linial showed that every d-regular graph has a 2-lift in which the additional eigenvalues are at most $O({\sqrt {d\log ^{3}d}})$ in magnitude.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] They also showed that if the starting graph is a good enough expander, then a good 2-lift can be found in polynomial time, thus giving an efficient construction of d-regular expanders for every d.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Bilu and Linial conjectured that the bound $O({\sqrt {d\log ^{3}d}})$ can be improved to $2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ , which would be optimal due to the Alon–Boppana bound.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] This conjecture was proved in the bipartite setting by Marcus, Spielman and Srivastava, who used the method of interlacing polynomials.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] As a result, they obtained an alternative construction of bipartite Ramanujan graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The original non-constructive proof was turned into an algorithm by Michael B.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Later the method was generalized to r-lifts by Hall, Puder and Sawin.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] There are many results that show the existence of graphs with good expansion properties through probabilistic arguments.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In fact, the existence of expanders was first proved by Pinsker who showed that for a randomly chosen n vertex left d regular bipartite graph, |*N*(*S*)| ≥ (*d* – 2)|*S*| for all subsets of vertices |*S*| ≤ *cdn* with high probability, where cd is a constant depending on d that is *O*(*d*-4).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Alon and Roichman showed that for every 1 > *ε* > 0, there is some *c*(*ε*) > 0 such that the following holds: For a group G of order n, consider the Cayley graph on G with *c*(*ε*) log2 *n* randomly chosen elements from G.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Then, in the limit of n getting to infinity, the resulting graph is almost surely an *ε*-expander.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In 2021, Alexander modified an MCMC algorithm to look for randomized constructions to produce Ramanujan graphs with a fixed vertex size and degree of regularity.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The results show the Ramanujan graphs exist for every vertex size and degree pair up to 2000 vertices.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In 2024 Alon produced an explicit construction for near Ramanujan graphs of every vertex size and degree pair.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The original motivation for expanders is to build economical robust networks (phone or computer): an expander with bounded degree is precisely an asymptotic robust graph with the number of edges growing linearly with size (number of vertices), for all subsets.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Expander graphs have found extensive applications in computer science, in designing algorithms, error correcting codes, extractors, pseudorandom generators, sorting networks (Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1983)) and robust computer networks.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] They have also been used in proofs of many important results in computational complexity theory, such as SL = L (Reingold (2008)) and the PCP theorem (Dinur (2007)).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In cryptography, expander graphs are used to construct hash functions.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In a 2006 survey of expander graphs, Hoory, Linial, and Wigderson split the study of expander graphs into four categories: extremal problems, typical behavior, explicit constructions, and algorithms.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Extremal problems focus on the bounding of expansion parameters, while typical behavior problems characterize how the expansion parameters are distributed over random graphs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Explicit constructions focus on constructing graphs that optimize certain parameters, and algorithmic questions study the evaluation and estimation of parameters.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The expander mixing lemma states that for an (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graph, for any two subsets of the vertices *S*, *T* ⊆ *V*, the number of edges between S and T is approximately what you would expect in a random d-regular graph.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The approximation is better the smaller *λ* is.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] In a random d-regular graph, as well as in an Erdős–Rényi random graph with edge probability *d*⁄*n*, we expect *d*⁄*n* • |*S*| • |*T*| edges between S and T.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] More formally, let *E*(*S*, *T*) denote the number of edges between S and T.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Many properties of (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graphs are corollaries of the expander mixing lemmas, including the following.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The Chernoff bound states that, when sampling many independent samples from a random variable in the range [−1, 1], with high probability the average of our samples is close to the expectation of the random variable.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The expander walk sampling lemma, due to Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1987) and Gillman (1998), states that this also holds true when sampling from a walk on an expander graph.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] This is particularly useful in the theory of derandomization, since sampling according to an expander walk uses many fewer random bits than sampling independently.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Sorting networks take a set of inputs and perform a series of parallel steps to sort the inputs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] A parallel step consists of performing any number of disjoint comparisons and potentially swapping pairs of compared inputs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The depth of a network is given by the number of parallel steps it takes.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Expander graphs play an important role in the AKS sorting network, which achieves depth *O*(log *n*).
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] While this is asymptotically the best known depth for a sorting network, the reliance on expanders makes the constant bound too large for practical use.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Within the AKS sorting network, expander graphs are used to construct bounded depth ε-halvers.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] An ε-halver takes as input a length n permutation of (1, …, *n*) and halves the inputs into two disjoint sets A and B such that for each integer *k* ≤ *n*⁄2 at most εk of the k smallest inputs are in B and at most εk of the k largest inputs are in A.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Following Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1983), a depth d ε-halver can be constructed as follows.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Take an n vertex, degree d bipartite expander with parts X and Y of equal size such that every subset of vertices of size at most εn has at least ⁠1 – *ε*/*ε*⁠ neighbors.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The vertices of the graph can be thought of as registers that contain inputs and the edges can be thought of as wires that compare the inputs of two registers.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] At the start, arbitrarily place half of the inputs in X and half of the inputs in Y and decompose the edges into d perfect matchings.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] The goal is to end with X roughly containing the smaller half of the inputs and Y containing roughly the larger half of the inputs.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] To achieve this, sequentially process each matching by comparing the registers paired up by the edges of this matching and correct any inputs that are out of order.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Specifically, for each edge of the matching, if the larger input is in the register in X and the smaller input is in the register in Y, then swap the two inputs so that the smaller one is in X and the larger one is in Y.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] It is clear that this process consists of d parallel steps.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] After all d rounds, take A to be the set of inputs in registers in X and B to be the set of inputs in registers in Y to obtain an ε-halving.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] To see this, notice that if a register u in X and v in Y are connected by an edge uv then after the matching with this edge is processed, the input in u is less than that of v.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Furthermore, this property remains true throughout the rest of the process.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Now, suppose for some *k* ≤ *n*⁄2 that more than εk of the inputs (1, …, *k*) are in B.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Then by expansion properties of the graph, the registers of these inputs in Y are connected with at least ⁠1 – *ε*/*ε*⁠*k* registers in X.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] Altogether, this constitutes more than k registers so there must be some register A in X connected to some register B in Y such that the final input of A is not in (1, …, *k*), while the final input of B is.
[src:pseudorandomness/expander-graph] This violates the previous property however, and thus the output sets A and B must be an ε-halving.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The random seed itself is typically a short binary string drawn from the uniform distribution.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Many different classes of statistical tests have been considered in the literature, among them the class of all Boolean circuits of a given size.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known whether good pseudorandom generators for this class exist, but it is known that their existence is in a certain sense equivalent to (unproven) circuit lower bounds in computational complexity theory.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Hence the construction of pseudorandom generators for the class of Boolean circuits of a given size rests on currently unproven hardness assumptions.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] These functions are the *statistical tests* that the pseudorandom generator will try to fool, and they are usually algorithms.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Sometimes the statistical tests are also called *adversaries* or *distinguishers*.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The notation in the codomain of the functions is the Kleene star.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The quantity $\ell$ is called the *seed length* and the quantity $n-\ell$ is called the *stretch* of the pseudorandom generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] In most applications, the family ${\mathcal {A}}$ represents some model of computation or some set of algorithms, and one is interested in designing a pseudorandom generator with small seed length and bias, and such that the output of the generator can be computed by the same sort of algorithm.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] In cryptography, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ usually consists of all circuits of size polynomial in the input and with a single bit output, and one is interested in designing pseudorandom generators that are computable by a polynomial-time algorithm and whose bias is negligible in the circuit size.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] These pseudorandom generators are sometimes called **cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators (CSPRGs)**.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known if cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Proving that they exist is difficult since their existence implies P ≠ NP, which is widely believed but a famously open problem.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators is widely believed.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] This is because it has been proven that pseudorandom generators can be constructed from any one-way function which are believed to exist.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators are necessary for many applications in cryptography.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generator theorem shows that cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist if and only if one-way functions exist.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators have numerous applications in cryptography.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] For instance, pseudorandom generators provide an efficient analog of one-time pads.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] It is well known that in order to encrypt a message *m* in a way that the cipher text provides no information on the plaintext, the key *k* used must be random over strings of length |m|.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Perfectly secure encryption is very costly in terms of key length.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Key length can be significantly reduced using a pseudorandom generator if perfect security is replaced by semantic security.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Common constructions of stream ciphers are based on pseudorandom generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators may also be used to construct symmetric key cryptosystems, where a large number of messages can be safely encrypted under the same key.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Such a construction can be based on a pseudorandom function family, which generalizes the notion of a pseudorandom generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Then in the 1990s, various idealizations of physics simulations—based on random walks, correlation functions, localization of eigenstates, etc., were used as tests of pseudorandom generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] NIST announced SP800-22 Randomness tests to test whether a pseudorandom generator produces high quality random bits.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Yongge Wang showed that NIST testing is not enough to detect weak pseudorandom generators and developed statistical distance based testing technique LILtest.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] A main application of pseudorandom generators lies in the derandomization of computation that relies on randomness, without corrupting the result of the computation.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Physical computers are deterministic machines, and obtaining true randomness can be a challenge.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators can be used to efficiently simulate randomized algorithms with using little or no randomness.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] In such applications, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ describes the randomized algorithm or class of randomized algorithms that one wants to simulate, and the goal is to design an "efficiently computable" pseudorandom generator against ${\mathcal {A}}$ whose seed length is as short as possible.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] If a full derandomization is desired, a completely deterministic simulation proceeds by replacing the random input to the randomized algorithm with the pseudorandom string produced by the pseudorandom generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The simulation does this for all possible seeds and averages the output of the various runs of the randomized algorithm in a suitable way.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] A fundamental question in computational complexity theory is whether all polynomial time randomized algorithms for decision problems can be deterministically simulated in polynomial time.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of such a simulation would imply that **BPP** = **P**.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] In 1991, Noam Nisan and Avi Wigderson provided a candidate pseudorandom generator with these properties.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] In 1997 Russell Impagliazzo and Avi Wigderson proved that the construction of Nisan and Wigderson is a pseudorandom generator assuming that there exists a decision problem that can be computed in time 2O(*n*) on inputs of length *n* but requires circuits of size 2Ω(*n*).
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] While unproven assumption about circuit complexity are needed to prove that the Nisan–Wigderson generator works for time-bounded machines, it is natural to restrict the class of statistical tests further such that we need not rely on such unproven assumptions.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] One class for which this has been done is the class of machines whose work space is bounded by $O(\log n)$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Using a repeated squaring trick known as Savitch's theorem, it is easy to show that every probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated in space $O(\log ^{2}n)$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Noam Nisan (1992) showed that this derandomization can actually be achieved with a pseudorandom generator of seed length $O(\log ^{2}n)$ that fools all $O(\log n)$ -space machines.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Nisan's generator has been used by Saks and Zhou (1999) to show that probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated deterministically in space $O(\log ^{1.5}n)$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] This result was improved by William Hoza in 2021 to space $O(\log ^{1.5}n/{\sqrt {\log \log n}})$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] When the statistical tests consist of all multivariate linear functions over some finite field $\mathbb {F}$ , one speaks of epsilon-biased generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The construction of Naor & Naor (1990) achieves a seed length of $\ell =\log n+O(\log(\epsilon ^{-1}))$ , which is optimal up to constant factors.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators for linear functions often serve as a building block for more complicated pseudorandom generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Viola (2008) proves that taking the sum of d small-bias generators fools polynomials of degree d .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Constant depth circuits that produce a single output bit.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generators used in cryptography and universal algorithmic derandomization have not been proven to exist, although their existence is widely believed.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Proofs for their existence would imply proofs of lower bounds on the circuit complexity of certain explicit functions.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generator] Such circuit lower bounds cannot be proved in the framework of natural proofs assuming the existence of stronger variants of cryptographic pseudorandom generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] That is, evaluating any low-degree polynomial at a point determined by the pseudorandom string is statistically close to evaluating the same polynomial at a point that is chosen uniformly at random.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] Pseudorandom generators for low-degree polynomials are a particular instance of pseudorandom generators for statistical tests, where the statistical tests considered are evaluations of low-degree polynomials.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] In other words, for every such polynomial $p(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ , the statistical distance between the distributions $p(U_{n})$ and $p(G(U_{\ell }))$ is at most a small $\epsilon$ , where $U_{k}$ is the uniform distribution over $\mathbb {F} ^{k}$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] The case $d=1$ corresponds to pseudorandom generators for linear functions and is solved by small-bias generators.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] For example, the construction of Naor & Naor (1990) achieves a seed length of $\ell =\log n+O(\log(\epsilon ^{-1}))$ , which is optimal up to constant factors.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] Bogdanov & Viola (2007) conjectured that the sum of small-bias generators fools low-degree polynomials and were able to prove this under the Gowers inverse conjecture.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] Lovett (2009) proved unconditionally that the sum of $2^{d}$ small-bias spaces fools polynomials of degree d .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] Viola (2008) proves that, in fact, taking the sum of only d small-bias generators is sufficient to fool polynomials of degree d .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandom-generators-for-polynomials] The analysis of Viola (2008) gives a seed length of $\ell =d\cdot \log n+O(2^{d}\cdot \log(\epsilon ^{-1}))$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] A **pseudorandom** sequence of numbers is one that appears to be statistically random, despite having been produced by a completely deterministic and repeatable process.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] The generation of random numbers has many uses, such as for random sampling, Monte Carlo methods, board games, or gambling.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In physics, however, most processes, such as gravitational acceleration, are deterministic, meaning that they always produce the same outcome from the same starting point.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] Some notable exceptions are radioactive decay and quantum measurement, which are both modeled as being truly random processes in the underlying physics.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] Since these processes are not practical sources of random numbers, pseudorandom numbers are used, which ideally have the unpredictability of a truly random sequence, despite being generated by a deterministic process.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In many applications, the deterministic process is a computer algorithm called a pseudorandom number generator, which must first be provided with a number called a random seed.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] Since the same seed will yield the same sequence every time, it is important that the seed be well chosen and kept hidden, especially in security applications, where the pattern's unpredictability is a critical feature.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In some cases where it is important for the sequence to be demonstrably unpredictable, physical sources of random numbers have been used, such as radioactive decay, atmospheric electromagnetic noise harvested from a radio tuned between stations, or intermixed timings of keystrokes.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] The time investment needed to obtain these numbers leads to a compromise: using some of these physics readings as a seed for a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] Before modern computing, researchers requiring random numbers would either generate them through various means (dice, cards, roulette wheels, etc.) or use existing random number tables.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] The first attempt to provide researchers with a ready supply of random digits was in 1927, when the Cambridge University Press published a table of 41,600 digits developed by L.H.C.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In 1947, the RAND Corporation generated numbers by the electronic simulation of a roulette wheel; the results were eventually published in 1955 as *A Million Random Digits with 100,000 Normal Deviates*.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In theoretical computer science, a distribution is **pseudorandom** against a class of adversaries if no adversary from the class can distinguish it from the uniform distribution with significant advantage.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] This notion of pseudorandomness is studied in computational complexity theory and has applications to cryptography.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] Formally, let *S* and *T* be finite sets and let **F** = {*f*: *S* → *T*} be a class of functions.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] A distribution **D** over *S* is ε-**pseudorandom** against **F** if for every *f* in **F**, the statistical distance between the distributions $f(X)$ and $f(Y)$ , where X is sampled from **D** and Y is sampled from the uniform distribution on *S*, is at most ε.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] In typical applications, the class **F** describes a model of computation with bounded resources and one is interested in designing distributions **D** with certain properties that are pseudorandom against **F**.
[src:pseudorandomness/pseudorandomness] The distribution **D** is often specified as the output of a pseudorandom generator.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] A **randomness extractor**, often simply called an "extractor", is a function, which being applied to output from a weak entropy source, together with a short, uniformly random seed, generates a highly random output that appears independent from the source and uniformly distributed.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Examples of weakly random sources include radioactive decay or thermal noise; the only restriction on possible sources is that there is no way they can be fully controlled, calculated or predicted, and that a lower bound on their entropy rate can be established.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] For a given source, a randomness extractor can even be considered to be a true random number generator (TRNG); but there is no single extractor that has been proven to produce truly random output from any type of weakly random source.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Sometimes the term "bias" is used to denote a weakly random source's departure from uniformity, and in older literature, some extractors are called **unbiasing algorithms**, as they take the randomness from a so-called "biased" source and output a distribution that appears unbiased.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The weakly random source will always be longer than the extractor's output, but an efficient extractor is one that lowers this ratio of lengths as much as possible, while simultaneously keeping the seed length low.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Intuitively, this means that as much randomness as possible has been "extracted" from the source.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] An extractor has some conceptual similarities with a pseudorandom generator (PRG), but the two concepts are not identical.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Both are functions that take as input a small, uniformly random seed and produce a longer output that "looks" uniformly random.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Some pseudorandom generators are, in fact, also extractors.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The min-entropy of a distribution X (denoted $H_{\infty }(X)$ ), is the largest real number k such that $\Pr[X=x]\leq 2^{-k}$ for every x in the range of X .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] In essence, this measures how likely X is to take its most likely value, giving a worst-case bound on how random X appears.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] For an *n*-bit distribution X with min-entropy *k*, we say that X is an $(n,k)$ distribution.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] In the above definition, *ε*-close refers to statistical distance.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Intuitively, an extractor takes a weakly random *n*-bit input and a short, uniformly random seed and produces an *m*-bit output that looks uniformly random.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The aim is to have a low d (i.e. to use as little uniform randomness as possible) and as high an m as possible (i.e. to get out as many close-to-random bits of output as we can).
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] An extractor is strong if concatenating the seed with the extractor's output yields a distribution that is still close to uniform.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] such that for every $(n,k)$ distribution X the distribution $U_{d}\circ {\text{Ext}}(X,U_{d})$ (the two copies of $U_{d}$ denote the same random variable) is $\epsilon$ -close to the uniform distribution on $U_{m+d}$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Using the probabilistic method, it can be shown that there exists a (*k*, *ε*)-extractor, i.e. that the construction is possible.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] However, it is usually not enough merely to show that an extractor exists.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] is an explicit (*k*, *ε*)-extractor, if Ext(*x*, *y*) can be computed in polynomial time (in its input length) and for every *n*, Ext*n* is a (*k*(*n*), *ε*(*n*))-extractor.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] A variant of the randomness extractor with weaker properties is the disperser.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] One of the most important aspects of cryptography is random key generation.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] It is often necessary to generate secret and random keys from sources that are semi-secret or which may be compromised to some degree.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] By taking a single, short (and secret) random key as a source, an extractor can be used to generate a longer pseudo-random key, which then can be used for public key encryption.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] More specifically, when a strong extractor is used its output will appear be uniformly random, even to someone who sees part (but not all) of the source.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] For example, if the source is known but the seed is not known (or vice versa).
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] This property of extractors is particularly useful in what is commonly called **Exposure-Resilient** cryptography in which the desired extractor is used as an **Exposure-Resilient Function** (ERF).
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The following paragraphs define and establish an important relationship between two kinds of ERF--***k*-ERF** and ***k*-APRF**--which are useful in Exposure-Resilient cryptography.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The goal is to construct an adaptive ERF whose output is highly random and uniformly distributed.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] But a stronger condition is often needed in which every output occurs with almost uniform probability.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] For this purpose **Almost-Perfect Resilient Functions** (APRF) are used.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Kamp and Zuckerman have proved a theorem stating that if a function f is a *k*-APRF, then f is also a *k*-ERF.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] More specifically, *any* extractor having sufficiently small error and taking as input an *oblivious*, bit-fixing source is also an APRF and therefore also a *k*-ERF.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] This lemma is proved by Kamp and Zuckerman.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The lemma is proved by examining the distance from uniform of the output, which in a $2^{-m}\epsilon (n)$ -extractor obviously is at most $2^{-m}\epsilon (n)$ , which satisfies the condition of the APRF.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The proof of this extractor's existence with $\delta \leq 1$ , as well as the fact that it is computable in linear computing time on the length of m can be found in the paper by Jesse Kamp and David Zuckerman (p.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] That this extractor fulfills the criteria of the lemma is trivially true as $\epsilon =2^{-cm}$ is a negligible function.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Since we know $\delta \leq 1$ then the lower bound on m is dominated by n .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] In the last step we use the fact that $\gamma \leq {\frac {1}{2}}$ which means that the power of n is at most 1 .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] And since n is a positive integer we know that $n^{2\gamma }$ is at most n .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Using this value of m we account for the worst case, where k is on its lower bound.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Perhaps the earliest example is due to John von Neumann.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] From the input stream, his extractor took bits, two at a time (first and second, then third and fourth, and so on).
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] If the two bits matched, no output was generated.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] If the bits differed, the value of the first bit was output.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The Von Neumann extractor can be shown to produce a uniform output even if the distribution of input bits is not uniform so long as each bit has the same probability of being one and there is no correlation between successive bits.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] To put it simply, because the bits are statistically independent and due to the commutative property of multiplication, it would follow that $P(A\cap B)=P(A)P(B)=P(B)P(A)=P(B\cap A)$ .
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Hence, if pairs of 01 and 10 are mapped onto bits 0 and 1 and pairs 00 and 11 are discarded, then the output will be a uniform distribution.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Iterations upon the Von Neumann extractor include the Elias and Peres extractor, the latter of which reuses bits in order to produce larger output streams than the Von Neumann extractor given the same size input stream.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Another approach is to use the output of a chaos machine applied to the input stream.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] This approach generally relies on properties of chaotic systems.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Input bits are pushed to the machine, evolving orbits and trajectories in multiple dynamical systems.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Thus, small differences in the input produce very different outputs.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Such a machine has a uniform output even if the distribution of input bits is not uniform or has serious flaws, and can therefore use weak entropy sources.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Additionally, this scheme allows for increased complexity, quality, and security of the output stream, controlled by specifying three parameters: *time cost*, *memory required*, and *secret key*.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Note that while true chaotic systems are mathematically sound for 'amplifying' entropy, this is predicated on the availability of real numbers with an infinite precision.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] When implemented in digital computers with finite precision number representation, as in chaos machines using IEEE 754 Floating-Point, the periodicity has been shown to fall far short of the full space for a given bit length.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] It is also possible to use a cryptographic hash function as a randomness extractor.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] However, not every hashing algorithm is suitable for this purpose.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Randomness extractors are used widely in cryptographic applications, whereby a cryptographic hash function is applied to a high-entropy, but non-uniform source, such as disk drive timing information or keyboard delays, to yield a uniformly random result.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Randomness extractors have played a major role in recent quantum cryptography developments, for example, distilling the raw output from a quantum random number generators into a shorter, secure and uniformly random output.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Strong extractors have proved useful in the generation of provable random numbers in commercial systems.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Recently, they have made it possible for the (near-perfect) randomness output from a quantum computer to be used to enhance the quality of randomness in remote systems which do not have access to a quantum computer.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] The ability to deliver randomness proven using quantum physics entirely in software would not be possible without the use of strong extractors.
[src:pseudorandomness/randomness-extractor] Randomness extraction is also used in some branches of computational complexity theory and in the construction of list-decodable error correcting codes.
